    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3920669737" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3920669737" />
    <a title="Viji" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9832129-viji"><img alt="Viji" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338206451p2/9832129.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3920669737?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Viji" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Viji" href="/user/show/9832129-viji">Viji</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9832129-viji?shelf=vijchatterbookreads2021">vijchatterbookreads2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3920669737" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16293336499189002755">If Karan Johar reads this book, he would say - &quot;kuch kuch hota hai, tum nahi samjhoge&quot;! At least that&apos;s what I feel after finishing it... a mixed state of emotions; a feeling of extreme satisfaction, and yet, a yearning for something more.<br/><br/>This book is a collection of 5 stories aptly titled Dharma, Shakti, Kama, Artha and Shanti - that has an ex-government official doubling up as a master story-teller, in the confines of an old-world bar in old-world Bombay.<br/><br/>Dharma and Shakti stay true to their ti</span>
  <span id="freeText16293336499189002755" style="display:none">If Karan Johar reads this book, he would say - "kuch kuch hota hai, tum nahi samjhoge"! At least that's what I feel after finishing it... a mixed state of emotions; a feeling of extreme satisfaction, and yet, a yearning for something more.<br /><br />This book is a collection of 5 stories aptly titled Dharma, Shakti, Kama, Artha and Shanti - that has an ex-government official doubling up as a master story-teller, in the confines of an old-world bar in old-world Bombay.<br /><br />Dharma and Shakti stay true to their title, and are my favorites. Chandra builds a strong plot in both, and keeps you engaged right till the very end. In Kama, we are introduced to Sartaj Singh (now famous because of Chandra's Sacred Games / Saif Ali Khan) and his characterization as the somber police officer with personal demons in his head, is very good in it, and it's his most fleshed-out character in the book. Artha, according to me, is the weakest story, followed by Shanti. Or maybe I just didn't get them.<br /><br />All through, what I found wonderful (as a Bombayite at heart maybe) was that, the city of Bombay is almost a hidden character, the quiet observer of the happenings in the stories... peeping out from circular balconies in Colaba, living in old 2-storey villas by the sea in Khar, coming alive in local trains and taxis, and showing you love by the rocks off Carter road. It's Bombay with its old-world beauty, hidden, like a gem, amidst the turmoil of the characters in the stories.<br /><br />Chandra's descriptive style is a bit tedious, and he adds too much detail to the narrative... as a reader, I would visualize the scene, and want to move on to the next part of the narrative, but I'm still being told about a ray of light here, a metal there etc. I found this laborious and tiring at times.<br /><br />However, and perhaps because of this, the narration very easily translates to a film script. It's all there... the landscape, the décor, the look and feel of the characters, the light, the camera angle... it's almost a film script hidden inside a book. I'm surprised it hasn't been made into an anthology film yet!<br /><br />Well, who knows, maybe if Karan Johar reads it, we'll get an "Ajeeb Dastaans in Bombay" soon! :)<br /><br />Rating: 3.5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="16293336499189002755" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

